				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">To Counter G.E., Japanese Company Mitsubishi May Join Siemens in Alstom Bid</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By David Jolly			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-06-11T14:41:24+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 11, 2014 10:41 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 11, 2014 10:41 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/11/business/dbpix-alstom/dbpix-alstom2-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/11/business/dbpix-alstom/dbpix-alstom2-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/11/business/dbpix-alstom/dbpix-alstom2-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002933184" width="592" height="395" alt="Alstom engineers work on a piece of a thermal reactor. Alstom is the leading maker of turbines for Franceâs nuclear industry."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Alstom engineers work on a piece of a thermal reactor. Alstom is the leading maker of turbines for Franceâs nuclear industry.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Jean-Pierre Muller/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/11/japanese-company-joins-siemens-in-potential-alstom-bid/" data-title="To Counter G.E., Japanese Company Mitsubishi May Join Siemens in Alstom Bid" data-description="A combined offer from Siemens and Mitsubishi Heavy Industries could ease antitrust concerns, but it was unclear how it would allay French worries about the fate of a national champion.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">PARIS â The German engineering conglomerate Siemens and Mitsubishi Heavy Industries of Japan said on Wednesday that they might bid jointly for Alstom, the French maker of power turbines and high-speed trains, as they seek to trump <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/28/france-softens-criticism-after-g-e-promises-jobs/" title=" A Thaw in France in G.E. Bid for Alstom (May 28, 2014)">a rival $13.5 billion offer from General Electric</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The two companies âhave joined forces in evaluating a potential proposal for certain assets of the French multinational conglomerate Alstom in order to strengthen the future position of Alstom, M.H.I. and Siemens,â they said in a joint statement.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Siemens, based in Munich and Berlin, has been encouraged by the French government to make an offer for Alstom, one of Franceâs industrial crown jewels, after <a href="//www.genewsroom.com/ge-offers-$13.5-billion-enterprise-value-to-acquire-alstom-thermal-renewables-and-grid-businesses-97385" title="G.E. press release">G.E.âs bid for Alstomâs power generation and transmission business</a>  met with a frosty reception  in Paris.</p>
		<div class="w190 right">
		<img src="//markets.on.nytimes.com/research/tools/builder/api.asp" width="190" height="250" alt=""/>		</div>
		
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To counter G.E.âs bid, which would leave Alstom as a stand-alone rail company, Siemens has suggested trading its own rail assets for Alstomâs power business, creating a German power giant and a French rail champion. But that idea has met with substantial skepticism among analysts and Alstom officials who think the antitrust hurdles would be insurmountable.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Siemens is itself in the middle of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/08/business/international/as-profit-rises-siemens-reorganizes-and-makes-deals.html" title="New York Times article">a painful restructuring and overhaul</a> of its energy business, and absorbing Alstom in a deal of such scale and complexity may be more than it can handle at the moment, analysts have said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The German company has set a deadline on Monday for making a formal offer for Alstom. The German and Japanese companies said on Wednesday that they would hold to that deadline, suggesting that their plans were well advanced.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Siemens declined to comment. Mitsubishi Heavy did not respond to requests for comment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They did not specify how they proposed to divide Alstomâs assets, but the entry into the picture of Mitsubishi Heavy creates the opportunity for Siemens to split off the parts of the company that are likely to invite regulatory scrutiny.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Siemens board will meet on Sunday to discuss the proposal, according to people briefed on the situation. Among the possibilities being considered is an arrangement under which Siemens obtains Alstom&#8217;s gas turbine business, they said, leaving Mitsubishi Heavy with Alstom&#8217;s power distribution and steam turbine businesses. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Such a deal could help to reduce regulators&#8217; concerns, according to the people, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The arrangement raises the possibility for new objections from President FranÃ§ois Hollande and Arnaud Montebourg, the economy minister, who are fighting to protect jobs and ensure that critical parts of Franceâs energy infrastructure remain where they are. It was not immediately clear how bringing in a Japanese company would contribute to the French goal of maintaining Alstom in some form as a European business.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âMr. Montebourg&#8217;s office declined to comment. â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The political dynamic appears to have changed from early days. Jeffrey R. Immelt, G.E.âs chairman and chief executive, has already sweetened his initial offer to bring government critics on board, adding job guarantees and signaling a willingness to involve French investors, winning qualified praise last month from Mr. Hollande.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe continue to have constructive discussions about the details of our proposed alliance with Alstom and remain confident,â G.E. said in a statement on Wednesday. âThe G.E.-Alstom alliance would build a global transport and energy leader in France, and create 1,000 new jobs for the people of France.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shunichi Miyanaga, Mitsubishi Heavyâs president and chief executive, said in the statement: âWe firmly believe that we can substantially contribute to a partnership solution for Alstom which will create value for all parties involved, including the country of France.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Christine Rahard-Burnat, a spokeswoman for Alstom, declined to comment, saying, &#8220;We haven&#8217;t received any formal offer yet.&#8221;</p>
<div id="addendums" class="addendums"><div class="story-addendum theme-correction"><strong>Correction: June 16, 2014</strong> <br>An earlier version of this article misspelled the given name of the chief executive of Mitsubishi Heavy Industries. He is Shunichi Miyanaga, not Shunishi.</div></div><footer class="story-footer">
    <div class="story-meta">
	<p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 06/12/2014, on page <span itemprop="printSection">B</span><span itemprop="printPage">6</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the headline: To Counter G.E., Japanese Company May Join Siemens in Alstom Bid.</p>    </div>
